  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Improving access to treatment &amp; support for people with epilepsy</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">In Sierra Leone, the devastating impact of epilepsy has left tens of thousands of children and adults outcast, living in extreme poverty. Complications such as malaria, meningitis and birth problems lead to many people developing epilepsy. Ignorance and stigma around the condition means that many people affected are committed to psychiatric hospitals and ostracised from schools and employment. Many epileptics suffer injuries and disabilities because of accidents during a fit, and some have to wait over five years for treatment. Through this project, children and adults with epilepsy will get life-changing support and treatment in Sierra Leone. The programme will train workers to counsel, advise and treat people with epilepsy. Awareness of the illness will be raised in schools, places of worship and communities to help people understand epilepsy and stop discrimination. Affected families will be supported to better understand the illness and workers in government clinics and hospitals will be trained to treat epilepsy patients. A media campaign will further raise public awareness. The project will also lobby government to provide money and services for effective epilepsy treatment. In addition to the project grant, Medical Assistance Sierra Leone has been awarded &#xA3;7000 to help strengthen the organisation and their work, enabling them to support their local partners in Africa to continue to provide effective solutions to the issues they address.</narrative>
  </description>
